Fronted by charismatic singer Adam Duritz, Counting Crows came out of the Bay Area in the early ‘90s with a classic-rock-influenced sound that couldn't have been more out of fashion in the era of grunge. But that helped them separate from the pack, and the band's 1993 debut album, August and Everything After, earned them huge success. Though Counting Crows have gone through quite a few line-up changes throughout the years, they've maintained their ever-devoted fanbase and, with Duritz at the helm, their signature sound.

As one of the younger pianists in the Blue Note stable, Horace Silver displays energy and confidence to match his nimble finger work on the keys. While his horn-obsessed peers were focused on solos, Silver is all about feel. He has the confidence to luxuriate in pauses, letting single notes hang in the air as long as the supporting groove is right. The possessor of a remarkable ear, he can say it all with just a few chords or a single repeated note: the high style of a man who wears songs like fine-cut clothing.

A titan of 20th-century American music, Johnny Cash's deep baritone voice, trademark style, anti-authoritarian slant, and huge catalog of genre-spanning songs made him one of the most important figures in country music. Over the course of a nearly five-decade career, The Man in Black dove into genres like rockabilly, rock 'n' roll, gospel, blues, and folk. After becoming one of country music's biggest stars in the ‘60s, the following decade saw his brooding image and gritty lifestyle, along with his traditionalist roots, help to launch the outlaw country movement and brand him as a rebel. In the ‘90s, with a lifetime of chart-topping songs and accolades, Cash teamed with rock producer Rick Rubin for a powerful series of albums that carried the touching weight of finality.

Meeting in the Illinois bar band scene of the late ‘60s, REO Speedwagon slowly made a name for themselves in the world of blues-based hard rock alongside groups like Bad Company and Foreigner. They released a prodigious nine albums between 1971 and 1979. By the ‘80s, they'd established themselves as purveyors of hooky riffs and bombastic anthems. The band crossed over to achieve mainstream success with a string of epic ballads released throughout the ‘80s, blurring the line between hard rock and soft rock. Speedwagon have slowed down their recording, but continue to tour successfully today.

Although there’s no shortage of stellar contemporary holiday tunes, there’s nothing quite like digging into the classics—the heartstring-tugging standards that conjure rosy-cheeked Santas, perfect gingerbread cookies, and Norman Rockwell’s idyllic scenes. With its focus on old-school hits sung by some of music’s most beloved postwar vocalists, this playlist is perfect for roasting chestnuts and reminiscing about the good old days.

Steely Dan's hyper-literate, jazzy art-rock has been captivating ears since the ‘70s. Their spacious, complex arrangements—helmed by Donald Fagen's often caustic lyrics—lead winding journeys through mellow horns and intricate guitar runs on “Deacon Blues,” engage funky bass on “Josie,” and pick up the pace with rollicking piano for the addictive “Reelin' In the Years.” Their impressive technical wizardry is balanced by killer grooves and pop sensibilities, turning a smoky, chilled-out tune like “Do It Again” into a perpetually diggable ride.
